			    STPJS 313</div>
  <p class="cont">give me my trespasses as I forgive those who trespass against me,<span class="footRef">1</span> for I freely forgive<span class="footRef">2</span> all men. If
  we would secure and cultivate the love of others,<span class="footRef">3</span> we must love others,<span class="footRef">4</span> even our enemies as well
  as friends.<span class="footRef">5</span></p>
  <p class="std">Sectarian priests cry out concerning me, and ask, &ldquo;Why is it this babbler<span class="footRef">6</span> gains so many
  followers,<span class="footRef">7</span> and retains them?&rdquo; I answer, It is because I possess the principle of love.<span class="footRef">8</span> All I can offer
  the world is a good heart and a good hand.<span class="footRef">9</span></p>
  <p class="std">The Saints can testify whether I am willing to lay down my life for my brethren.<span class="footRef">10</span> If it has been
  demonstrated that I have been willing to die for a &ldquo;Mormon,&rdquo; I am bold to declare before Heaven
  that I am just as ready to die in defending the rights of a Presbyterian, a Baptist, or a good man of
  any other denomination; for the same principle which would trample upon the rights of the
  Latter-day Saints would trample upon the rights of the Roman Catholics, or of any other
  denomination who may be unpopular and too weak to defend themselves.<span class="footRef">11</span></p>
  <div class="topic">Love of Liberty</div>
  <p class="std">It is a love of liberty<span class="footRef">12</span> which inspires my soul&mdash;civil and religious liberty to the whole of the
  human race. Love of liberty was diffused into my soul by my grandfathers while they dandled me
  on their knees;<span class="footRef">13</span> and shall I want friends? No.</p>
  <p class="std">The inquiry is frequently made of me. &ldquo;Wherein do you differ from others in your religious
  views?&rdquo; In reality and essence we do not differ so far in our religious views, but that we could all
  drink<span class="footRef">14</span> into one principle of love. One of the grand fundamental principles of &ldquo;Mormonism&rdquo; is to
  receive truth,<span class="footRef">15</span> let it come from whence it may.</p>
  <p class="std">We believe in the Great Elohim who sits enthroned in yonder heavens. So do the Presbyterians.
  If a skilful mechanic, in taking a welding heat, uses borax, alum, etc., and succeeds in welding
  together iron or steel more perfectly than any other mechanic, is he not deserving of praise? And if
  by the principles of truth I succeed in uniting men of all denominations in the bonds of love,<span class="footRef">16</span> shall
  I not have attained a good object?<span class="footRef">17</span></p>
  <p class="std">If I esteem mankind to be in error, shall I bear them down? No. I will lift them up,<span class="footRef">18</span> and in their
  own way too, if I cannot persuade them<span class="footRef">19</span> my way is better; and I will not seek to compel any man
  to believe as I do, only by the force of reasoning, for truth will cut its own way.<span class="footRef">20</span> Do you believe
  in Jesus Christ and</p>
